35	Alternative 3, 6-Lane, Pacific Interchange	  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Arial">This alternative provides a new interchange east of the existing Montlake Blvd/520 interchange. It also includes a new roadway from this intersection across Union Bay to another new interchange at Pacific   St. and Montlake   Blvd. near the UW Husky Stadium.</span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial">(Source: WSDOT SR 520 DEIS, appendix X: &ldquo;<span>Pacific Street Interchange Option &ndash; Screening and Location Analysis</span>,&rdquo; <a href="http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/NR/rdonlyres/14488A89-4A53-44C1-AEE1-22F99A53F73D/0/SR520DEIS_AppendixX.pdf">http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/NR/rdonlyres/14488A89-4A53-44C1-AEE1-22F99A53F73D/0/SR520DEIS_AppendixX.pdf</a>)</span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Arial"> </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Arial">Outside of these details this Alternative is substantially mirrors the 6-Lane Alternative. This alternative &ldquo;will include six lanes (two outer general purpose lanes and one inside HOV lane in each direction).&rdquo; <br /> <br /> &ldquo;SR 520 will be rebuilt from I-5 to 108th   Avenue Northeast in Bellevue, with an auxiliary lane added on SR 520 eastbound east of I-405 to 124th   Avenue Northeast. Both the Portage Bay and Evergreen Point bridges will be replaced.&rdquo; <br /> <br /> &ldquo;A 14-foot-wide bicycle/pedestrian path will be built along the north side of SR 520 through Montlake and the Evergreen  Point Bridge and along the south side of SR 520 through the Eastside to 96th Avenue Northeast. <br /> <br /> Noise walls will be built along much of SR 520 in Seattle and the Eastside. This alternative will include stormwater treatment and electronic toll collection. <br /> <br /> This alternative will also add five 500-foot-long lids to be built across SR 520 to reconnect communities along SR 520: Roanoke, North Capitol Hill, Portage Bay, Montlake, Medina, Hunts Point, Clyde Hill, and Yarrow Point. The lids will be located at 10th Avenue East and Delmar Drive East, Montlake Boulevard, Evergreen Point Road, 84th Avenue Northeast, and 92nd Avenue Northeast. <br /> <br /> The floating bridge pontoons of the Evergreen  Point Bridge will be sized to carry future high capacity transit (HCT). The alternative does not include an HCT alignment. A flexible transportation plan (FTP) will provide funding to promote alternative modes of travel and increase the efficiency of the system, including intelligent transportation and technology, traffic systems management, vanpools and transit, education and promotion, and land use as demand management.&rdquo;</span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial">(Source: WSDOT project Web Page, summary description, <a href="http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/Projects/SR520Bridge/Plans/4_Lane.htm">http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/Projects/SR520Bridge/Plans/4_Lane.htm</a>)</span></p>  	Rebuild the SR 520 Bridge with a new bridge across the ship canal to Pacific St. near Husky Stadium			10008	<p><a href="http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/projects/SR520Bridge/" title="WSDOT Project Homepage">WSDOT Project Homepage</a></p><p><a href="http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/Projects/SR520Bridge/Library.htm" title="Library of EIS/technical documents">Library of EIS/technical documents</a></p><p><a href="http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/NR/rdonlyres/14488A89-4A53-44C1-AEE1-22F99A53F73D/0/SR520DEIS_AppendixX.pdf" title="Pacific Street Interchange Technical Memorandum">Pacific Street Interchange Technical Memorandum</a></p>	2712999936	WSDOT	0	\N	\N	32	0	0	0	King	0	0
81	University of Washington to Mountlake Terrace	  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Arial">This project would construct a 10.2 mile extension of Link light rail from the UW station to Mountlake Terrace. The project begins with construction of a 4.3-mile extension of Link light rail from the UW station to Northgate. The right-of-way would include a mix of tunnels and elevated guideway. North of the UW station the route crosses under the campus west of 15<sup>th</sup>   Ave. NE and north along Brooklyn Ave. to an underground station at NE 45<sup>th</sup> St. and Brooklyn. It then continues north on Brooklyn Ave. &ldquo;North of NE 50th Street, the alignment shifts to the west and then passes beneath NE Ravenna Boulevard and continues north generally west of and parallel to 12th Avenue NE.&rdquo; &ldquo;The alignment continues north along the west side of 12th Avenue NE to the underground Roosevelt Station located between NE 65th Street and NE 68th Street.&rdquo; It then turns west, moves above ground and generally follows the I-5 right-of-way. North of 95<sup>th</sup> St. the alignment transitions to an elevated guideway eventually reaching &ldquo;an elevated Northgate Station spanning NE 103rd</span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Arial">Street.&rdquo;</span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Arial"> </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Arial">From Northgate the alignment continues for 2.1 miles on an aerial alignment along the east side of I-5 to a Jackson Park Station at NE 145<sup>th</sup>   St. The station would include 500 structured parking spaces. The alignment would then continue 2.4 miles on the east side of I-5 to a similar Shoreline Station at NE   185<sup>th</sup> St. before continuing an additional 1.4 miles to the Mountlake Terrace Station at NE 236<sup>th</sup> St. Sound walls would be provided as necessary. &ldquo;The final alignment and station locations will be determined through project level design and environmental review.&rdquo;</span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial">(Source: Sound Transit project page for N06, N28, N29, N30 found at: <a href="http://soundtransit.org/x3951.xml">http://soundtransit.org/x3951.xml</a>)</span></p>  	Construct an extension of Link light rail from UW to Mountlake Terrace			10042	<p><a href="http://soundtransit.org/Documents/pdf/st2/potential_projects_01_04_2007/N06_-Link-_University_of_Washington_to_Northgate_DP.pdf" title="Sound Transit Project Page: UW to Northgate">Sound Transit Project Page: UW to Northgate</a></p><p><a href="http://soundtransit.org/Documents/pdf/st2/potential_projects_01_04_2007/N28_-Link-_Northgate_to_Jackson_Park_DP.pdf" title="Sound Transit Project Page: Northgate to Jackson Park">Sound Transit Project Page: Northgate to Jackson Park</a> </p><p><a href="http://soundtransit.org/Documents/pdf/st2/potential_projects_01_04_2007/N29_-Link-_Jackson_Park_to_Shoreline_DP.pdf" title="Sound Transit Project Page: Jackson Park to Shoreline">Sound Transit Project Page: Jackson Park to Shoreline</a> </p><p><a href="http://soundtransit.org/Documents/pdf/st2/potential_projects_01_04_2007/N30_-Link-_Shoreline_to_Mountlake_Terrace_DP.pdf" title="Sound Transit Project Page: Shoreline to Mountlake Terrace">Sound Transit Project Page: Shoreline to Mountlake Terrace</a></p><p><a href="http://soundtransit.org/x3951.xml" title="Map and list of potential transit projects">Map and list of potential transit projects</a></p><p><a href="http://www.soundtransit.org/x1694.xml" title="Sound Transit north light rail homepage">Sound Transit north light rail homepage</a></p><p><a href="http://www.soundtransit.org/x3009.xml" title="North light rail Final Supplemental Environmental Impact Statement">North light rail Final Supplemental Environmental Impact Statement</a></p><p><a href="http://www.soundtransit.org/x1755.xml" title="Brooklyn Station: info and graphics">Brooklyn Station: info and graphics</a></p><p><a href="http://www.soundtransit.org/x1695.xml" title="Roosevelt Station: info and graphics">Roosevelt Station: info and graphics</a></p><p><a href="http://www.soundtransit.org/x1697.xml" title="Northgate Station: info and graphics">Northgate Station: info and graphics</a></p>	2161200128	Sound Transit	0	\N	\N	79	0	0	0	King	0	0
28	Alternative 1, Elevated Structure	  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Arial">At the south end of the project beginning at S. Walker St. and continuing to the beginning of the existing elevated structure at S. Dearborn St. the project would be a six-lane at-grade roadway, including various connections to south downtown, and adjustments for access to the Whatcom Railyard.</span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial">(Source: Paraphrased from SDEIS, pg. 41-43, <a href="http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/NR/rdonlyres/0DD5A623-51A0-4118-B4CF-F1B2147D3138/0/SDEISChapter4TheAlternatives.pdf">http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/NR/rdonlyres/0DD5A623-51A0-4118-B4CF-F1B2147D3138/0/SDEISChapter4TheAlternatives.pdf</a>.)</span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Arial"> </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Arial">Beginning shortly after S. Royal Brougham Way &ldquo;the Elevated Structure Alternative replaces the existing structure with a stacked aerial structure along the central waterfront. For the most part, the new aerial structure would have three lanes in each direction, and it would have wider lanes and shoulders than the existing viaduct. Between S. King Street and the ramps at Columbia and Seneca Streets, SR 99 would have four lanes in each direction. The existing ramps at Columbia and Seneca Streets would be rebuilt.</span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Arial"> </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Arial">The new elevated structure would be 11.5 to 35 feet wider than the existing viaduct from south of S. Main Street up to Union Street. Near S. King Street to south of S. Main Street, the elevated structure would be 54 to 74 feet wider than the existing viaduct as SR 99 transitions from a side-by-side at grade roadway in the south to a new double-level elevated structure. <em>(SDEIS, Page 19)</em></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Arial"> </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Arial">The Battery Street Tunnel would be improved by adding emergency exits, upgrading the electrical system, building a fire suppression system, and improving the ventilation system.</span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Arial"> </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Arial">A new Alaskan Way surface street would function on the surface as it does today, with additional turn-lane improvements and the Waterfront Streetcar. Constructing the Elevated Structure over Elliott and Western Avenues, with an enhanced northbound exit from the structure to Western Avenue and an enhanced southbound entrance from Elliott to SR 99, maintains access and mobility for Ballard and Interbay residents.&rdquo; </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial">(Source: Seattle DOT, <a href="http://seattle.gov/mayor/issues/viaduct/pdf/Overviews.pdf">http://seattle.gov/mayor/issues/viaduct/pdf/Overviews.pdf</a>, pg. 3.)</span></p>  	Replace the Viaduct in its existing location with an aerial structure			10006	<p><a href="http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/projects/Viaduct/" target="_blank" title="WSDOT Project Homepage">WSDOT Project Homepage</a></p><p><a href="http://www.seattle.gov/transportation/awv.htm" title="Seattle DOT Project Homepage">Seattle DOT Project Homepage</a></p><p><a href="http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/Projects/Viaduct/Library.htm#technicaldocuments" title="Library of EIS/technical documents">Library of EIS/technical documents</a></p><p><a href="http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/NR/rdonlyres/0DD5A623-51A0-4118-B4CF-F1B2147D3138/0/SDEISChapter4TheAlternatives.pdf" title="Descriptions/Maps of Alternatives">Descriptions/Maps of Alternatives</a></p><p><a href="http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/Projects/Viaduct/animations.htm" title="Aninmations of Alternatives">Aninmations of Alternatives</a></p>	416500000	WSDOT	0	\N	\N	27	0	0	0	King	0	0
